  "source": "[m \\:less.than.or.equal:/ n]\nDescribes: m\nwhen: n is \\set.theoretic.natural.number\nextends: m is \\set.theoretic.natural.number\nsatisfies:\n. anyOf:\n  . m \\:less.than?:/ n\n  . m = n\nDocumented:\n. called: \"less than or equal to\"\n. written: \"m? \\leq n?\"\n. description: \"For natural numbers, $m \\leq n$ means $m < n$ or $m = n$; equivalently $m \\subseteq n$. This order is transitive, inheriting transitivity from the subset relation.\"\nId: \"fb02b92c-b803-414e-b46c-a882237acf3d\"",
